WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.600
My name is Kirill.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:13.320
Today I present you first results from my collaboration with duckdb labs and posit.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:19.320
I wouldn't be here today if not for Hannes and Tom and Davis, Hadley, Andrew and Kevin.

00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:22.180
And thank you for joining me in this presentation.

00:00:22.180 --> 00:00:27.280
So duckdb, we have heard in case you missed the previous talk, is the new high performance

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:33.680
database that works in R, in Python, in Java, JavaScript, Rust, Swift, Scala, I don't know,

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:34.680
everywhere.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:36.680
And it integrates with Arrow.

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:42.560
dplyr, this is example code using the taxi data that Hannes just shown.

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:53.240
It computes the median tip percentage by passenger count in the state of cab rides in New York

00:00:53.240 --> 00:01:00.560
City in 2019, 1.7 gigabyte compressed, more if you uncompress this, and you can load

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:08.360
this into memory, you can use dplyr to compute this, but have you actually tried to do things

00:01:08.360 --> 00:01:11.239
with such a large dataset in dplyr?

00:01:11.239 --> 00:01:12.239
I feel uneasy.

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:13.239
I'm not very patient.

00:01:13.239 --> 00:01:15.040
This takes eight seconds on my machine.

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:18.540
And spoiler alert, with duckdplyr it is going to be much faster.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:22.879
But before we get to the how, let me start with why.

00:01:23.519 --> 00:01:27.919
So I get a lot of joy of writing and reading dplyr code.

00:01:27.919 --> 00:01:34.120
Even if you're not familiar with the syntax, you can read from top to bottom, you can see

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:41.400
what each individual step is doing, and you can execute parts of the pipeline to inspect

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:44.120
intermediate results.

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:48.599
Now this is a SQL version of the same query.

00:01:48.599 --> 00:01:52.080
The order of operations is mixed up.

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:57.959
And to run a simplified version of this thing for, I don't know, debugging, you would have

00:01:57.959 --> 00:01:59.459
to carefully edit it.

00:01:59.459 --> 00:02:06.339
So I find for incremental building and debugging, dplyr is easier, is better.

00:02:06.339 --> 00:02:09.360
Now a feature matrix could look like this.

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:11.679
We have dplyr, which is nice, but slower.

00:02:11.679 --> 00:02:15.279
We have duckdb, which uses SQL, but it's super fast.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:17.839
Hannes spent like 20 minutes on explaining why.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:24.880
Multi-threading native code and the queries, it sees the queries and it optimizes them

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:30.119
as a whole, and to end, chooses the best way to compute the desired result.

00:02:30.119 --> 00:02:36.080
Maybe the most important thing, Hannes and his team, talented database specialists with

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:40.320
decades of experience, and this is their day job, this is what they do day in, day out,

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:44.759
making DuckDB faster and faster and faster and ever faster.

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:46.960
So can we have the icing and the cake?

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:48.679
Can we have fast dplyr?

00:02:48.679 --> 00:02:51.360
Yes, this has worked before.

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:57.839
With dbplyr, we can take dplyr code, convert it into SQL, run it on the database, get it

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:02.679
back as a data frame, continue operating in R.

00:03:02.679 --> 00:03:07.360
And there are other such systems, such as datatable and dtplyr.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:13.880
There is arrow, there is collapse, there may be more that are implementing the dplyr syntax.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.000
What is wrong here?

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.320
Well, we inherit too many features from the underlying database.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:27.800
DuckDB can read parquet, this is great, dbplyr can also read parquet, duckdb works with datasets

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:33.320
larger than memory, perfect, dbplyr works with datasets larger than memory, but when

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:39.000
we get the data from dbplyr, it's not a data frame, we have to collect it, transform it

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:40.559
into a data frame.

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:46.679
We don't support all the R functions, we don't support all the R data types, and for some

00:03:46.679 --> 00:03:52.440
functions even the implementation or the semantics are a little different, bottom line chances

00:03:52.440 --> 00:04:01.199
are your dplyr code, if you take it and try to run this with dbplyr, will not work out

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:02.479
of the box.

00:04:02.479 --> 00:04:09.800
Now unlike duckdplyr, duckdplyr is designed as a full drop-in replacement for dplyr, data

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:13.000
frame in, data frame out.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:21.079
Support for all data types, all R functions, I mean, yes, we try to do things in duckdb,

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:31.519
if we can't we just offload to dplyr and handle it there without breaking your code.

00:04:31.559 --> 00:04:38.880
My goal is to make all of your dplyr code work with duckdplyr and make more and more

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:46.480
of your code work faster so that you can focus on what matters to you and achieve better

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:51.839
results in less time, development time, and computation time.

00:04:51.839 --> 00:04:56.480
And now this is me working on duckdplyr, so tests are green, everything passes, we need

00:04:56.480 --> 00:05:02.079
a new feature, maybe we go to Hannes and ask them to build something, sometimes it's

00:05:02.079 --> 00:05:08.480
the other way around, duckdb changes behavior, it challenges my expectations, but it's a

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:16.079
lot of fun iterating between correctness, performance, and completeness.

00:05:16.079 --> 00:05:22.200
So working on duckdplyr is test-first development, except the tests already exist, we don't need

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:28.959
to write them, we have 3,500 test cases in the dplyr package, and we can adapt them to

00:05:28.959 --> 00:05:32.959
run against duckdplyr.

00:05:32.959 --> 00:05:39.359
And we have 4,000 packages on CRAN that use dplyr directly or indirectly.

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:48.239
We can create a modified version of dplyr that uses duckdplyr and see what happens with

00:05:48.239 --> 00:05:50.119
those packages.

00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:57.880
So the combination here helps us find the occasional bug and also guide our development

00:05:57.880 --> 00:05:58.880
efforts.

00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:01.079
This is great.

00:06:01.079 --> 00:06:09.519
Now if you've been in Davis's talk, dotpy is the new kid on the block for group operations.

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:17.679
Groupby we do not support, this is laziness, this is because we want you to use the new

00:06:17.679 --> 00:06:22.359
syntax and frankly fewer things can go wrong this way.

00:06:22.359 --> 00:06:26.559
Now what happens if you compare an integer with a string?

00:06:26.559 --> 00:06:28.760
What happens when you compare an integer with a factor?

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:32.200
On what day of week does the week start?

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:40.320
And R and duckdb have different opinions here and on many, many other questions.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:45.679
This is why we support only a small subset of the functions right now.

00:06:45.679 --> 00:06:49.679
This is more opt-in than opt-out.

00:06:49.679 --> 00:06:51.839
We know how to handle those.

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:59.040
All this now takes us time to implement basically the rest of that.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:03.579
Now one more difference is row order.

00:07:03.579 --> 00:07:11.980
So if you think about a data frame, you sort a data frame by a specific column in dplyr

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:16.579
and if there are ties, if there are multiple rows with the same value, the original order

00:07:16.579 --> 00:07:21.619
of rows will be preserved with dplyr and duckdb just doesn't care.

00:07:21.619 --> 00:07:26.420
Because duckdb cares about performance, they might just shuffle around your rows.

00:07:26.420 --> 00:07:32.899
This is why we have two modes of operation, a slower mode that will maintain the original

00:07:32.899 --> 00:07:39.839
row order and fast mode that will do whatever duckdb is doing here.

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:44.619
And we'll see which one will be most useful in the end.

00:07:44.619 --> 00:07:49.739
Now speaking about performance, I did not dare to make a live demo, but I'm showing

00:07:49.739 --> 00:07:54.700
you how this looks like in the RStudio IDE.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:57.100
Now this starts in a clean R session.

00:07:57.100 --> 00:08:02.100
I'm attaching the dplyr, I'm attaching the duckdplyr package and I'm using conflicted

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:07.299
here to reduce the noise and to be very specific about the functions I use.

00:08:07.299 --> 00:08:11.980
If you're not familiar with that, I highly recommend this for your scripts.

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:19.359
This is the same query I had in the beginning, the taxi data ingestion preparation summary

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:24.459
and I'm running this in three statements and these take no time.

00:08:24.459 --> 00:08:27.299
Push, push, push.

00:08:27.299 --> 00:08:33.219
They're done immediately and this is because nothing has been actually computed here.

00:08:33.219 --> 00:08:38.780
You see in the bottom the results, just don't know the number of rows just yet.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:47.419
These are data frames, lazy data frames, but these are proxies and they need to be computed

00:08:47.419 --> 00:08:50.260
in order to be available as full data frames.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:56.059
Yet they have a class, the class is DataFrame and the subclass, they have column names,

00:08:56.059 --> 00:08:59.020
they have column types, just not the data yet.

00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:08.020
I can use DuckDB internals to see what will happen when the query is actually executed.

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:12.539
So this is a lot of output and it reads from bottom to top.

00:09:12.539 --> 00:09:18.260
So we start at the bottom with ingesting the parquet file and we read only the columns

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:22.460
that we need and only the rows that we need.

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:28.059
Further along the way there is this transformation computation of percentages, there is the grouping

00:09:28.059 --> 00:09:35.340
operation and there is the ordering of the output and all of this from start to finish

00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:39.500
runs as a single DuckDB operation.

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:42.219
Data mentions fast, we'll see.

00:09:42.219 --> 00:09:47.859
So running this, touching a column, querying, getting the value of a column actually triggers

00:09:47.859 --> 00:09:48.859
the computation.

00:09:48.859 --> 00:09:51.159
Again, this output is huge.

00:09:51.159 --> 00:09:54.640
In the middle you see the vector, 987 and so forth.

00:09:54.640 --> 00:09:58.719
That's the regular R vector that comes back from this operation.

00:09:58.719 --> 00:10:06.880
At the top we see the recipe, that's what DuckDB is using to compute the result.

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:11.299
And the structure of the output, this can be turned off, I feel for now it's useful

00:10:11.299 --> 00:10:13.260
to have this on.

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:22.179
Because I used system time in the code I see it took 1.8 seconds to run and in the user

00:10:22.179 --> 00:10:29.460
column 5 seconds of computation time, meaning more than one core, more than one processor

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:31.739
was involved multi-threading.

00:10:31.739 --> 00:10:38.059
Now we're doing this a second time or we are accessing the full data frame, this is instantaneous

00:10:38.299 --> 00:10:43.380
because once we have computed it we do not need to do this again, of course.

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:49.140
If we compare this with a more traditional deploy workflow like loading the data and

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:55.179
then doing the computation, the taxi data variable, that's the first.

00:10:55.179 --> 00:11:00.780
I get the number of rows, this also triggers the computation.

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:04.340
And this is now all the columns and it takes four seconds and doing the whole analysis

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:05.340
took two.

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:10.140
So, well, I think that's already an improvement.

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:20.140
The arrow, the refresh thing in the environment pane now actually is useful, clicking on it

00:11:20.140 --> 00:11:27.539
shows for the data sets that we have touched how many rows there are and we see taxi data

00:11:27.539 --> 00:11:32.179
prep that was the preparation has not even been materialized yet.

00:11:32.179 --> 00:11:37.299
We don't need this because the result has been computed from end-to-end with FTP.

00:11:37.299 --> 00:11:44.299
Now this has been recorded for the very recent and as in nightly built version of their Studio

00:11:44.299 --> 00:11:45.299
IDE.

00:11:45.299 --> 00:11:47.940
I'm not sure if this is in the release yet.

00:11:47.940 --> 00:11:55.859
Maybe you need manual refresh only in your version of the IDE or of the Positive Workbench.

00:11:55.859 --> 00:11:59.580
So we run this with a few other queries.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:05.219
The query I showed was fastest in dplyr, all the variants with more groups or that

00:12:05.219 --> 00:12:12.739
included join with dimension table take about 20 seconds or more.

00:12:12.739 --> 00:12:15.659
In dplyr, all of this runs in less than two seconds.

00:12:15.659 --> 00:12:21.419
In duckplyr, in order of magnitude, just like that, I really like this particular result.

00:12:21.419 --> 00:12:24.419
So completeness.

00:12:24.419 --> 00:12:28.340
One thing we do not support yet is custom R functions.

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:32.700
If we had a code like this, and this might take a second to digest.

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:40.059
So instead of computing inline, we would implement a compute PCT function that can be the percentage.

00:12:40.059 --> 00:12:43.979
This will not be handled by DuckDB, still it will work.

00:12:43.979 --> 00:12:49.859
So what's going to happen here, mutate from duckplyr function, we'll see a compute PCT,

00:12:49.859 --> 00:12:55.940
I don't know what that is, I send it to dplyr and dplyr will just do it.

00:12:55.940 --> 00:13:03.460
It will call compute PCT, query the value of the column, and by querying the column,

00:13:03.460 --> 00:13:13.700
it will actually start computation of the filter, which still will be in DuckDB duckplyr.

00:13:13.700 --> 00:13:21.820
So this will work, a bit slower, but still you don't have to change your code at all,

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:23.780
I hope.

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:30.340
Now there is work to do, we would like to support more data frames, especially maybe

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:35.219
spatial data frames would be useful, Hannes mentioned nested and packed columns, actually

00:13:35.219 --> 00:13:41.140
they do work in DuckDB, they just don't work in duckplyr yet.

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:46.539
More R functions, more data types, ideally all R functions, all data types, we'll see

00:13:46.539 --> 00:13:50.280
if we can get to there.

00:13:50.280 --> 00:13:57.280
We have a good idea why we're doing this, we have a good idea how to do this, now we

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:01.679
only need to know what, and for this we will need your help.

00:14:01.679 --> 00:14:06.719
You can install this today, it is on Cron, the binaries have been built, all this will

00:14:06.719 --> 00:14:14.119
do is get you an updated version of dplyr and DuckDB in case you need it, it won't otherwise

00:14:14.119 --> 00:14:16.119
change your system.

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:21.840
And there are two basic ways to use this first, as duckplyr df, you write this as the

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:31.679
first step in your pipes and this will run the dplyr steps in duckplyr, but you have

00:14:31.679 --> 00:14:34.599
to do this with every pipe you have.

00:14:34.599 --> 00:14:43.000
If you're courageous, methods override will send everything to duckplyr, and this will

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:49.919
reset when you restart the R session, and there's also a function to turn it off.

00:14:49.919 --> 00:14:58.280
This is the GitHub, I would love to hear if this works for your code, file an issue, drop

00:14:58.280 --> 00:15:04.239
me a line, we have a presence in the lobby and I'd be happy to take questions here.

00:15:04.239 --> 00:15:05.239
Thank you.

00:15:05.239 --> 00:15:13.880
Thank you.

00:15:13.880 --> 00:15:17.440
We have five minutes until the next talk so we have plenty of time for questions, so please

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:19.679
do submit them on Slido if you have them.

00:15:19.679 --> 00:15:26.359
I have a question, is the goal to one day support 100% compatibility with dplyr, including

00:15:26.359 --> 00:15:28.599
things like groupby?

00:15:28.599 --> 00:15:31.840
Including things like groupby.

00:15:31.880 --> 00:15:39.280
I wouldn't place bets on groupby, but for the other parts of the question, yes.

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:46.080
If you find that something that works in dplyr does not work in duckplyr, this is a bug,

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:50.159
because we really strive to near full compatibility.

00:15:50.159 --> 00:15:57.599
I know this is elusive, because the slope gets very, very steep at the end, but I don't

00:15:57.599 --> 00:16:01.000
want to put a figure on it.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.039
We will look at everything that you send our way.

00:16:04.039 --> 00:16:06.020
Sounds good.

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:10.960
Do list columns in data frames work with duckplyr?

00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:14.599
Come back next month.

00:16:14.599 --> 00:16:17.119
Nice quick answer, I like it.

00:16:17.119 --> 00:16:23.919
Is there an advantage using duckplyr alone versus starting with a tbl, converting that

00:16:24.039 --> 00:16:30.000
tbl to an arrow table and piping it to arrow to duckdb?

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.159
You can do that.

00:16:31.159 --> 00:16:36.960
One thing I forgot to mention, indeed, that you do not have to start with a parquet file.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:40.799
Hannes said this too, you can start with a data frame, I just didn't have the data in

00:16:40.799 --> 00:16:44.520
memory just yet in my demo, which is why I got this straight from the parquet, and this

00:16:44.520 --> 00:16:47.140
also gave a nice speed up.

00:16:47.140 --> 00:16:50.880
You can start with data frames, you can start with arrow, you can start with csv, with parquet,

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:58.000
with anything that duckdb can ingest, and we have a function that allows you to read

00:16:58.000 --> 00:16:59.679
those files.

00:16:59.679 --> 00:17:01.599
That's great.

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:06.400
What is on the roadmap for duckplyr that you are most excited about?

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:11.640
Definitely nested and packed columns, and this is the low-hanging fruit, I think, and

00:17:11.640 --> 00:17:19.479
well, yeah, I'd say.

00:17:19.479 --> 00:17:24.040
I think that's all the questions I have, so let's give a hand again to Kirill for his

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:25.040
talk.

